aws::graph::propositions: # Cessna 172 Aircraft Accident in Fresno, California
The accident occurred in Fresno, California.
The accident occurred on May 2, 2020, at 09:30 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a Cessna 172.
The defining event was loss of engine power (partial).
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Personal.
The accident number was WPR20LA136.
The aircraft registration was N734NW.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
The accident resulted in 1 minor injury.
Shortly after takeoff on runway 30, the airplane reached about 300 to 400 ft above ground level.
The engine lost partial power at 300 to 400 ft above ground level.
The pilot prepared for a downwind landing to runway 12.
The pilot realized the airplane had excess energy.
The pilot deployed the flaps.
The pilot performed a forward slip maneuver.
The airplane touched down about halfway down the runway.
The airplane continued off the end of the runway.
The airplane went through a fence.
The airplane passed over two westbound lanes of a road.
The airplane nosed over in the median.
Examination of the engine revealed low compression on two of the six cylinders.
Cylinder number 3 had approximately 25 to 75 percent compression loss.
Cylinder number 5 had approximately 25 to 75 percent compression loss.
The valve rocker arms were tapped with a rubber mallet.
Compression recovered to approximately 25 percent loss in cylinder number 3.
Compression recovered to approximately 15 percent loss in cylinder number 5.
An internal borescope examination of the engine cylinders was conducted.
The piston tops appeared normal.
The cylinder sidewalls appeared normal.
No evidence of foreign object ingestion was observed.
No other pre-impact mechanical anomalies were identified during the examination.
The reason for the low compression could not be determined.
The engine was disassembled 1.9 hours before the accident flight.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of this accident.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Fresno, California

## Date & Time: 
May 2, 2020, 09:30 Local

## Aircraft:
Cessna 172

## Defining Event:
Loss of engine power (partial)

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Personal

## Accident Number:
WPR20LA136

## Registration:
N734NW

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
1 Minor

## Analysis

Shortly after takeoff on runway 30, as the airplane reached about 300 to 400 ft above ground level, the engine lost partial power. The pilot prepared for a downwind landing to runway 12 and when he realized the airplane had excess energy, he deployed the flaps and performed a forward slip maneuver. The airplane touched down about halfway down the runway and continued off the end and through a fence. The airplane then passed over the two westbound lanes of a road and nosed over in the median.

Examination of the engine revealed low compression on two of the six cylinders (around 25 to 75 percent compression loss on cylinder numbers 3 and 5). The valve rocker arms were tapped with a rubber mallet and compression recovered to approximately 25 percent loss in the number 3 cylinder and 15 percent loss in the number 5 cylinder. An internal borescope examination of the engine cylinders revealed the piston tops and cylinder sidewalls appeared normal and no evidence of foreign object ingestion was observed. No other pre-impact mechanical anomalies were identified during the examination.

Although the reason for the low compression could not be determined, it was noted that the engine was disassembled 1.9 hours before the accident flight.
